  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Sacrificial Rite for the Grand Minister Yi Kong, Called Yugyeong
  author: Yi Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this month and day, behold—how luminous your spirit shines, possessed of such open-hearted breadth. Heaven granted you this measure of soul. With each day's distant stride, one might have thought longevity assured. Yet why did fate snatch away your years so violently?

    Truly, when rank rises high, men guard their bodies jealously. When stipends grow fat, they cling to life. They husband their frames with care, scheming for long years ahead. This is reason's course, the human heart's own law. But you, my friend, were otherwise. You held not life as precious, nor office as honor. Your body, you regarded as a borrowed lodging merely. With all things you sought no contention.

    You would point your finger to your lips and say: "Let me drink wine." Day upon day you drank without measure—what care had you for your wasting flesh? When others drink, they savor only the taste. But you—you dwelt within the wine itself, caring nothing for your own keeping. Through such disregard, you departed far too soon.

    Alas! All is ended now. How can words avail?

    This offering lacks fine delicacies—only fragrant wine remains. Yet what the heart cherishes needs not distinguish between this world and the next. Drink deep, honored one, and answer back my grief.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Kong (李公) likely refers to a high-ranking official of the Goryeo dynasty; 'Yugyeong' (惟卿) was probably his courtesy name or honorific.
  - key: ''
    value: The image of pointing to one's mouth to indicate drinking is a classical gesture of nonchalance and philosophical indifference to material concerns.
  - key: ''
    value: The distinction between 幽明 (yu-myeong, 'dark and light' or 'this world and the next') suggests the poet's belief that the deceased's spirit transcends the boundary between life and death.
